  <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_6_1">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        A standard parameterization for the unit circle is <m>\langle \cos(t), \sin(t) \rangle</m>, for <m>0 \le t \le 2\pi</m>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a vector-valued function <m>\vr</m> that describes a point traveling along the unit circle so that at time <m>t=0</m> the point is at <m>\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}, \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \right)</m> and travels clockwise along the circle as <m>t</m> increases.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\langle \sin(t + \frac{\pi}{4}), \cos(t + \frac{\pi}{4}) \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          For an initial point of <m>\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}, \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \right)</m>, the initial inputs must be <m>\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</m>. Therefore, <m>\langle sin(t + \frac{\pi}{4}), cos(t + \frac{\pi}{4}) \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a vector-valued function <m>\vr</m> that describes a point traveling along the unit circle so that at time <m>t=0</m> the point is at <m>\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}, \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \right)</m> and travels counter-clockwise along the circle as <m>t</m> increases.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\langle \cos(t + \frac{\pi}{4}), \sin(t + \frac{\pi}{4}) \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          In order for the circle to be traced in the counter-clockwise direction, we need to switch <m>x(t)</m> and <m>y(t)</m>. Therefore, <m>\langle \cos(t + \frac{\pi}{4}), \sin(t + \frac{\pi}{4}) \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a vector-valued function <m>\vr</m> that describes a point traveling along the unit circle so that at time <m>t=0</m> the point is at <m>\left(-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}, \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \right)</m> and travels clockwise along the circle as <m>t</m> increases.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\langle \sin(t - \frac{\pi}{4}), \cos(t - \frac{\pi}{4}) \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          In order for the circle to have an initial point at <m>\left(-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}, \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \right)</m>, the input for <m>\sin(t)</m> and <m>\cos(t)</m> must be <m>-\frac{\pi}{4}</m>. Therefore <m>\langle \sin(t - \frac{\pi}{4}), \cos(t - \frac{\pi}{4}) \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a vector-valued function <m>\vr</m> that describes a point traveling along the unit circle so that at time <m>t=0</m> the point is at <m>(0,1)</m> and makes one complete revolution around the circle in the counter-clockwise direction on the interval <m>[0,\pi]</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\langle \cos(2t), \sin(2t) \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The period of the function must be <m>\pi</m>. Therefore, <m>\langle \cos(2t), \sin(2t) \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="circle-param">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        You might recall the pythagorean identity from trigonometry given by
        <md>\cos^2(\theta)+\sin^2(\theta)=1</md>
        We want to use this identity to parameterize the circle with center <m>(h,k)</m> and radius <m>r \gt 0</m> given by
        <md> (x-h)^2 + (y-k)^2 = r^2 </md>
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Reorganize the general equation of a circle 
          <md> (x-h)^2 + (y-k)^2 = r^2 </md>
          to be of the form
          <md> (\underline{\hspace{1in.}})^2+(\underline{\hspace{1in.}})^2=1</md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <md> (\frac{x-h}{r})^2+(\frac{y-k}{r})^2=1</md>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
           <md> (\frac{x-h}{r})^2+(\frac{y-k}{r})^2=1</md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Because identities work for any value, we can use the pythagorean identity to parameterize the general equation of a circle. Fill in the blanks below with each of the respective quantities from the previous task
          <md>
            <mrow>\cos(t) = \amp \underline{\hspace{1in.}} </mrow>
            <mrow>\sin(t) = \amp \underline{\hspace{1in.}} </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\cos(t) = \frac{x-h}{r} </mrow>
            <mrow>\sin(t) = \frac{y-k}{r} </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\cos(t) = \frac{x-h}{r} </mrow>
            <mrow>\sin(t) = \frac{y-k}{r} </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve each of the two equations from the previous part for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> to get parametric equations for a generalized circle. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>x(t)=r\cos(t) +h </mrow>
            <mrow>y(t)=r\sin(t) +k </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>x(t)=r\cos(t) +h </mrow>
            <mrow>y(t)=r\sin(t) +k </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write a couple sentences about what <m>r</m>, <m>h</m>, and <m>k</m> mean in the parametric equations for a generalized circle. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The parameter <m>r</m> stretches both the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> coordinates by <m>r</m> and the parameters <m>h</m> and <m>k</m> shift the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> coordinates.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="ellipse_param">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="circle-param"/>, we saw that to parametrize the implicit equation of a circle with center <m>(h,k)</m> and radius <m>r \gt 0</m> given by
        <md> (x-h)^2 + (y-k)^2 = r^2 </md>
        we can use the relationship between <m>\sin</m> and <m>\cos</m>. We found a parametric equations for the generalized circle can be expressed by 
        <md>x(t) =r \cos(\theta) + h \qquad y(t) = r \sin(\theta) + k</md>
        The conic section most closely related to the circle is the ellipse. The general equation of an ellipse (centered at the origin) is given by
        <md> \frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} = 1.</md>
      </p>
      <p>
        We can continue to make use of the relationship between <m>\sin</m> and <m>\cos</m> to discover parametric equations for an ellipse. In fact, without the <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> in the equation things would work perfectly. To remedy this (that is, get rid of <m>a,b</m>) we simply multiply by <m>\sin</m> and <m>\cos</m> by these values. Consider the equations
        <md>x(t) = a \cos(t) \qquad y(t) = b \sin(t). </md>
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Substitute the equations for <m>x(t), y(t)</m> above into
        <md> \frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2}</md>
        and simplify.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <md>
            \frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} = 1
          </md>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            \frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} = \frac{(a \cos(t))^2}{a^2} + \frac{(b\sin(t))^2}{b^2} =\cos^2(t)+\sin^2(t)=1
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the ellipse given by <m> \frac{x^2}{9} + \frac{y^2}{4} = 1.</m> What are the parametric equations for this ellipse?  Graph them below to ensure you obtain the exact same graph.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="ellipse_desmos">
          <caption>A Desmos Interactive for <xref ref="ellipse_param"/></caption>
          <interactive desmos="dlwiulbqe7" width="100%" aspect="1:1"/>
        </figure>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>x(t)= 3 \cos(t)</m> and <m>y(t)=2 \sin(t)</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>x(t)= 3 \cos(t)</m> and <m>y(t)=2 \sin(t)</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In <xref ref="ellipse_desmos"/>, update the equation in <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> as well as the parametric equations for the ellipse <m>\frac{x^2}{16} + \frac{y^2}{25} = 1.</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>x(t)= 4 \cos(t)</m> and <m>y(t)=5 \sin(t)</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>x(t)= 4 \cos(t)</m> and <m>y(t)=5 \sin(t)</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write a few sentences about the orientation of the parametric equations given as your answer for the previous couple of tasks. In particular, you should talk about the following: at what point do you "start", i.e. what point corresponds to <m>t=0</m>? How do you move around the ellipse (clockwise or counterclockwise)?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          Start at the right most point and travels counterclockwise.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          For each of the parameterizations given, the point corresponding to <m>t=0</m> will be the right-most point on the ellipse. All of these parameterizations move counterclockwise around the ellipse.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Update your equations in <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> from part (c), as well as the parametric equations that were your answer to part (c), so that the ellipse has a center of <m>(-2,1)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>x(t)= 4 \cos(t)-2</m> and <m>y(t)=5 \sin(t)+1</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>x(t)= 4 \cos(t)-2</m> and <m>y(t)=5 \sin(t)+1</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Since we know that
          <md> (\cos(t))^2 +(\sin(t))^2=1 \quad \text{for every }t\in\mathbb{R}</md>
          and the form of a translated ellipse is given by
          <md>\frac{(x-h)^2}{a^2} + \frac{(y-k)^2}{b^2} = 1,</md>
          set
          <md>\frac{(x-h)^2}{a^2}=(\cos(t))^2</md>
          and solve for x.
        </p>
        <p>
          Set up a similar equation involving <m>y</m> and <m>\sin(t)</m> then solve for <m>y</m> to get a general set of parametric equations for the translated ellipse.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>x(t)= a \cos(t) +h</m> and <m>y(t)=b \sin(t)+k</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>x(t)= a \cos(t)+h</m> and <m>y(t)=b \sin(t)+k</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_6_2">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be positive real numbers. You have probably seen the equation <m>\frac{(x-h)^2}{a^2} + \frac{(y-k)^2}{b^2} = 1</m> that generates an ellipse, centered at <m>(h,k)</m>, with a horizontal axis of length <m>2a</m> and a vertical axis of length <m>2b</m>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write a few sentences to explain why the vector function <m>\vr</m> defined by <m>\vr(t) = \langle a\cos(t), b\sin(t) \rangle</m>, <m>0 \le t \le 2\pi</m> is a parameterization of the ellipse <m>\frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} = 1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>a \cos(t)</m> traces the values from <m>x = a</m> to <m>x = -a</m> and back to <m>x = a</m> for <m> 0 \leq t \leq 2 \pi</m>. <m>b \sin(t)</m> traces the values from <m>y = 0</m> to <m>y = b</m> to <m>y = -b</m> and back to <m>y = 0</m> for <m>0 \leq t \leq 2 \pi</m>. 
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>a \cos(t)</m> traces the values from <m>x = a</m> to <m>x = -a</m> and back to <m>x = a</m> for <m> 0 \leq t \leq 2 \pi</m>. <m>b \sin(t)</m> traces the values from <m>y = 0</m> to <m>y = b</m> to <m>y = -b</m> and back to <m>y = 0</m> for <m>0 \leq t \leq 2 \pi</m>. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a parameterization of the ellipse <m>\frac{x^2}{4} + \frac{y^2}{16} = 1</m> that is traversed clockwise.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(t) = \langle 2 \cos(-t), 4\sin(-t) \rangle</m> or <m>\vr(t) = \langle 2\sin(t), 4\cos(t) \rangle</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(t) = \langle 2 \cos(-t), 4\sin(-t) \rangle</m> or <m>\vr(t) = \langle 2\sin(t), 4\cos(t) \rangle</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a parameterization of the ellipse <m>\frac{(x+3)^2}{4} + \frac{(y-2)^2}{9} = 1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(t) = \langle 2\cos(t) - 3, 3\sin(t) + 2 \rangle</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>\cos^2(t) = \frac{(x + 3)^2}{4}</m>. Solve for <m>x</m> to get <m>x = 2\cos(t) - 3</m>. <m>sin^2(t) = \frac{(y - 2)^2}{9}</m>. Solve for <m>y</m> to get <m>y = 3\sin(t) + 2</m>. Therefore <m>\vr(t) = \langle 2\cos(t) - 3, 3\sin(t) + 2 \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine the <m>xy</m>-equation of the ellipse that is parameterized by
          <md>
            \vr(t) = \langle 3 + 4\sin(2t), 1 + 3\cos(2t) \rangle.
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{(x-3)^2}{16} + \frac{(y-1)^2}{1} = 1</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>x = 3 + 4sin(2t)</m>. Solve for <m>sin(2t)</m> to get <m>\frac{x - 3}{4} = sin(2t)</m>. Square both sides to get <m>\frac{(x - 3)^2}{16} = sin^2(2t)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>y = 1 + 2cos(2t)</m>. Solve for <m>cos(2t)</m> to get <m>\frac{y - 1}{1} = cos(2t)</m>. Square both sides to get <m>\frac{(y - 1)^2}{1} = cos^2(2t)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          The equation for the ellipse is <m>\frac{(x-3)^2}{16} + \frac{(y-1)^2}{1} = 1</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_6_3">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        In this exercise, we will examine the graph of <m>z = 3x^2 + 4y^2 - 2</m>. You do not need to know what this graph looks like, but we will look at the intersection of this graph with several types of fundamental planes.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine a vector-valued function <m>\vr</m> that parameterizes the curve which is the <m>x = 2</m> trace of <m>z = 3x^2 + 4y^2 - 2</m>.  Plot the resulting curve. Do likewise for <m>x = -2, -1, 0,</m> and <m>1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
           Let <m>a</m> represent the <m>x</m>-value trace. The vector-valued functions are of the form <m>\vr(t) = \langle a, t, 3a^2 + 4t^2 - 2 \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let <m>a</m> represent the <m>x</m>-value trace. The vector-valued functions are of the form <m>\vr(t) = \langle a, t, 3a^2 + 4t^2 - 2 \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine a vector-valued function <m>\vr</m> that parameterizes the curve which is the <m>y = 2</m> trace of <m>z = 3x^2 + 4y^2 - 2</m>.  Plot the resulting curve.  Do likewise for <m>y = -2, -1, 0,</m> and <m>1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          Let <m>b</m> represent the <m>y</m>-value trace. The vector-valued functions are of the form <m>\vr(t) = \langle t, b, 3t^2 + 4b^2 - 2 \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let <m>b</m> represent the <m>y</m>-value trace. The vector-valued functions are of the form <m>\vr(t) = \langle t, b, 3t^2 + 4b^2 - 2 \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine a vector-valued function <m>\vr</m> that parameterizes the curve which is the <m>z = 2</m> contour of <m>z = 3x^2 + 4y^2 - 2</m>.  Plot the resulting curve.  Do likewise for <m>z = -2, -1, 0,</m> and <m>1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          Let <m>c</m> represent the <m>z</m>-value level curve, and use <m>cos^2(t)</m> and <m>sin^2(t)</m> for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> respectively.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(t) = \langle \sqrt{\frac{c + 2 - 4\sin^2(t)}{3}}, \sqrt{\frac{c + 2 - 3\cos^2(t)}{4}} \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let <m>c</m> represent the <m>z</m>-value level curve, and use <m>\cos^2(t)</m> and <m>\sin^2(t)</m> for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> respectively. Then <m>c + 2 - 4\sin^2(t) = 3\cos^2(t)</m>. Solve for <m>\cos(t)</m> to get <m>\sqrt{\frac{c + 2 - 4\sin^2(t)}{3}}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Also <m>c + 2 - 3cos^2(t) = 4sin^2(t)</m>. Solve for <m>sin(t)</m> to get <m>\sqrt{\frac{c + 2 - 3cos^2(t)}{4}}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Therefore, <m>\vr(t) = \langle \sqrt{\frac{c + 2 - 4\sin^2(t)}{3}}, \sqrt{\frac{c + 2 - 3\cos^2(t)}{4}} \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the traces and contours you've just investigated to create a wireframe plot of the surface generated by <m>z = 3x^2 + 4y^2 - 2</m>.  In addition, write a couple sentences to describe the characteristics of the surface.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The traces in the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> directions are parabolas. The contours are circles whose radii increase as <m>z</m> increases. The surface is an upward facing paraboloid that is shifted up two units on the z-axis. 
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The traces in the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> directions are parabolas. The contours are circles whose radii increase as <m>z</m> increases. The surface is an upward facing paraboloid that is shifted up two units on the z-axis. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    
  </exercise>
  <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_6_4">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Recall that any line in space may be represented parametrically by a vector-valued function.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a vector-valued function <m>\vr</m> that parameterizes the line through <m>(-2,1,4)</m> in the direction of the vector <m>\vv = \langle 3, 2, -5 \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(t) = \langle -2 + 3t, 1 + 2t, 4 - 5t \rangle</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(t) = \langle -2 + 3t, 1 + 2t, 4 - 5t \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a vector-valued function <m>\vr</m> that parameterizes the line of intersection of the planes <m>x + 2y - z = 4</m> and <m>3x + y - 2z = 1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(t) = \langle t, \frac{1}{3}t + \frac{7}{3}, \frac{5}{3}t + \frac{14}{3} \rangle</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Solve the first equation for <m>z</m> to get <m>z = x + 2y - 4</m>. Substiture into the second equation to get <m>3x + y - 2(x + 2y -4) = 1</m>. Solve for <m>y</m> to get <m>y = \frac{1}{3}x + \frac{7}{3}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Let <m>x = t</m>. Then <m>y = \frac{1}{3}t + \frac{7}{3}</m>. Substitute these equations into <m>z = x + 2y -4</m> to get <m>z = \frac{5}{3}t + \frac{14}{3}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Therefore, <m>\vr(t) = \langle t, \frac{1}{3}t + \frac{7}{3}, \frac{5}{3}t + \frac{14}{3} \rangle</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you let <m>y = t</m>, you would get <m>\vr(t) = \langle -7 + 3t, t, -11 + 5t \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine the point of intersection of the lines given by
          <md>
            x = 2 + 3t, \ y = 1 - 2t, \ z = 4t,
          </md>
          <md>
            x = 3 + 1s, \ y = 3-2s, \ z = 2s.
          </md>
          Then, find a vector-valued function <m>\vr</m> that parameterizes the line that passes through the point of intersection you just found and is perpendicular to both of the given lines.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          The point of intersection is <m>(5, -1, 4)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(t) = \langle 5 + 4t, -1 - 2t, 4 - 4t \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Set the <m>x</m> equations equal to each other, set the <m>y</m> equations equal to each other, and set the <m>z</m> equations equal to each other. <m>2 + 3t = 3 + s, 1 - 2t = 3 - 2s, 4t = 2s</m>. Solve the system using substitution to get <m>s = 2, t = 1</m>. Plug either <m>s = 2</m> into the first set of parametric equations or <m>t = 1</m> into the second set of parametric equations to get the point <m>(5, -1, 4)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the line in (a), the direction vector is <m>\langle 3, -2, 4 \rangle</m>. The direction vector of the second line is <m>\langle 1, -2, 2 \rangle</m>. Find the cross product between these two vectors to get the normal vector <m>\langle 4, -2, -4 \rangle</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Therefore, <m>\vr(t) = \langle 5 + 4t, -1 - 2t, 4 - 4t \rangle</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="Ez_9_6_5">
    <introduction>
      <p>
        For each of the following, describe the effect of the parameter <m>s</m> on the parametric curve for <m>t</m> in the interval <m>[0,2 \pi]</m>. 
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(t) = \langle \cos(t), \sin(t) + s \rangle</m> 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>s</m> shifts the curve left and right.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>s</m> shifts the curve left and right.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(t) = \langle \cos(t)-s, \sin(t) \rangle</m> 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>s</m> shifts the curve left and right.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>s</m> shifts the curve left and right.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(t) = \langle s\cos(t), \sin(t) \rangle</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>s</m> stretches/shrinks the graph in the <m>x</m> direction.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>s</m> stretches/shrinks the graph in the <m>x</m> direction.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(t) = \langle s\cos(t), s\sin(t) \rangle</m> 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>s</m> stretches/shrinks the graph in the <m>y</m> direction.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>s</m> stretches/shrinks the graph in the <m>y</m> direction.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\vr(t) = \langle \cos(st), \sin(st) \rangle</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>s</m> determines how far around the circle the curve is graphed.
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>s</m> determines how far around the circle the curve is graphed.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="hyperbola_param">
    <title>Parameterizing a Translated Hyperbola</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Another conic section that will be useful to quickly parameterize is the hyperbola. The translated hyperbola is given by 
        <md number="yes" xml:id="hyp_eq"> \frac{(x-h)^2}{a^2} - \frac{(y-k)^2}{b^2} = 1</md>
        for horizontal orientation and
        <md number ="yes" xml:id="hyp_eq2"> \frac{(y-k)^2}{a^2} - \frac{(x-h)^2}{b^2} = 1</md>
        for vertical orientation.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task xml:id="hyp_trig">
      <statement>
      <p>
        Find a trig identity (using the variable <m>t</m>) of the form
        <md> (\underline{\hspace{0.5in}})^2-(\underline{\hspace{0.5in}})^2=1</md>
      </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Look for one involving secant and tangent.
        </p>
      </hint>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>\sec^2(t)-\tan^2(t)=1</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Set the first blank element of your trig identity (<m>(\underline{\hspace{0.5in}})^2</m>) from the previous part equal to 
          <md>\frac{(x-h)^2}{a^2}</md>
          and then solve for <m>x</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>x(t) = a \sec (t)+h</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>x(t) = a \sec (t)+h</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Set up a similar equation involving <m>y</m> and the trig function from the second blank of <xref ref="hyp_trig"/> then solve for <m>y</m> to get a general set of parametric equations for the translated hyperbola.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>x(t) = a \sec (t)+h</m> and <m>y(t) = b \tan(t)+k</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>x(t) = a \sec (t)+h</m> and <m>y(t) = b \tan(t)+k</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>
        Substitute in your parametric equations for the translated hyperbola (your answers for parts (b) and (c) above) into the Desmos Interactive below. You should check that your equations trace the same graph as the translated hyperbola. You should move the sliders for <m>h</m>, <m>k</m>, <m>a</m>, and <m>b</m> to convince yourself that this set of parametric equations works for all cases (of the horizontal orientation).
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="hyperbola_desmos">
        <caption>A Desmos Interactive for <xref ref="hyperbola_param"/></caption>
        <interactive desmos="xxhji8sfzx" width="100%" aspect="1:1"/>
      </figure>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        For each of the following equations, give a parameterization and be sure state the bounds of your parameterization.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{(x-2)^2}{9}+\frac{(y+1)^2}{16}=1</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>x(t)= 3 \cos(t) +2</m> and <m>y(t)= 4 \sin(t)-1</m> with <m>t \in [0,2\pi)</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>x(t)= 3 \cos(t) +2</m> and <m>y(t)= 4 \sin(t)-1</m> with <m>t \in [0,2\pi)</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{(y+3)^2}{4}-\frac{(x+1)^2}{9}=1</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>x(t) = 3 \tan(t)-1</m> and <m>y(t) = 2 \sec(t) -3</m> with <m>t \in [0,2\pi)</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>x(t) = 3 \tan(t)-1</m> and <m>y(t) = 2 \sec(t) -3</m> with <m>t \in [0,2\pi)</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>(y-7)^2=-4(x+1)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>x(t)= -\frac{(t-7)^2}{4}-1</m> and <m>y(t) = t</m> for <m>t \in \mathbb{R}</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>x(t)= -\frac{(t-7)^2}{4}-1</m> and <m>y(t) = t</m> for <m>t \in \mathbb{R}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exercise>

